To what hath been ſaid, may be added this Conſideration, That when the best Phyſicians are baffled by ſome Diſtempers, they adviſe their Patients to uſe the Water of ſome Mineral Spring; tacitly acknowledging thereby, that all their Preſcriptions may be excell'd by Water. They pretend indeed, to aſcribe its Effects to ſome Minerals with which the Waters are Tinctur'd: But Dr. Baynard, in pag 438. of Sir John Floyer's Cold Bathing, tells of a certain Perſon who uſed to frequent Tunbridge, by which he found much Benefit; but being hindered from going thither one Seaſon did drink the ſame Quantities of Water taken from the Pump of a Spring in his own Yard, which did him as much Service: Whereupon he wrote thus on his Pump:


The Steel is a Cheat;

'Tis Water does the Feat.
